    {
      "id": "bce13d86_15300d1c",
      "file_path": "feature-server-pool/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/serverpool/Keyword.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 187,
      "message": "Clearly, it did pass checkstyle -- maybe it allows '_' if you have camel-case as well. This code used to be part of 'buildReflectiveLookup', and the method name 'lookupClassByName' doesn't describe what it does. I am using the '_' notation to indicate that this method is logically part of 'buildReflectiveLookup', and wouldn't exist as a separate method if we didn't have this Sonar !@#$% to deal with.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 743,
        "name": "Ralph Straubs",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "rs8887@att.com",
        "username": "rs8887"
      },
      "updated": "2020-05-11 12:44:06.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "73de9625_f5cb1f3b",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "b111e2b0_31d392b1",
      "file_path": "feature-server-pool/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/serverpool/Server.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 1040,
      "message": "I wonder what the logic is behind that? 'final' does keep the intermediate code from reassigning an object, but it doesn't prevent it from mucking around with the object.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 743,
        "name": "Ralph Straubs",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "rs8887@att.com",
        "username": "rs8887"
      },
      "updated": "2020-05-11 12:44:06.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "68bc9214_d434fb53",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "7c24ff43_ee4231f7",
      "file_path": "feature-server-pool/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/serverpool/TargetLock.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 2725,
      "message": "I know -- that constraint doesn't make any sense to me. I was planning on ignoring that one. Aren't multiple breaks/continues within a loop comparable to having multiple return points in a method?\n\nAt one point, structured programming advocates were claiming that you should only have one return per function or method. I did get into the habit of doing this, where possible -- code like:\n\nif (condition)\n  {\n     error leg ...\n  }\nelse\n  {\n     success leg ...\n  }\n\nrather than:\n\nif (condition)\n  {\n     error leg ...\n     return\n  }\nsuccess leg ...\n\nAs you have indicated, ONAP now prefers the latter, because 'success leg' has one less level of nesting, and sonar doesn't like nesting.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 743,
        "name": "Ralph Straubs",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "rs8887@att.com",
        "username": "rs8887"
      },
      "updated": "2020-05-11 12:44:06.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "7531c487_f3492630",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
